<p class="">Hon. Members opposite had better quarrel with their leader and not with me. Lack of preparation, forsooth !<p></p> The right hon. Gentleman then got on to another horse of a different kind. He complained about the frequent changes amongst Service Ministers. Whether they are frequently changed or not, the right hon. Gentleman said they were no good anyhow. [HON. MEMBERS: "Hear, hear."] Just a feeble "Hear, hear"? I expected louder applause after that observation. The right hon. Gentleman commented that we were not appointed, myself in particular, on grounds of public interest, that our appointment was not dictated by public considerations. I would like to ask the right hon. Gentleman a question. He is in the dock now, not I. No doubt he will furnish a reply. Was the appointment of the right hon. Gentleman the Member for Bournemouth (Mr. Bracken) as First <span id="2115" class="column-number" data-column-number="2115"></span> Lord of the Admiralty and the appointment of Mr. Duncan Sandys as Minister of Works dictated by public interest?</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
